Scrum uses the Sprint as a containing event for four formal events: 

Sprint Planning
Daily Scrum
Sprint Review
Sprint Retrospective

These events build the empirical Scrum pillars: 
transparency (making work visible)
inspection (evaluating progress) and 
adaptation (changing course to improve).

The four formal events and how they apply these pillars include:

1. Sprint Planning

What it is: A meeting to launch the Sprint.
The Goal: Decide what to build and how to build it.
Inspect & Adapt: The team inspects the Product Backlog and adapts it into the Sprint Backlog to define the Sprint Goal.

2. Daily Scrum
What it is: A quick, 15-minute daily team meeting.
The Goal: Check if the team is on track for their goals.
Inspect & Adapt: The team inspects progress toward the Sprint Goal and adapts the daily plan.

3. Sprint Review
What it is: An informal meeting at the end of the Sprint.
The Goal: Share what the team built with stakeholders.
Inspect & Adapt: The team inspects the Increment (the work done) and adapts the Product Backlog for future Sprints based on feedback.

4. Sprint Retrospective
What it is: A meeting to look at how the team worked.
The Goal: Improve how the team works together.
Inspect & Adapt: The team inspects their methods, people, and tools, then adapts by creating plans for improvement in the next Sprint.